NAME
    grep - search for patterns in input

SYNOPSIS
    grep [options] <pattern> [file...]
    <input> | grep [options] <pattern>

DESCRIPTION
    Searches for lines matching a regular expression pattern.
    Reads from files or stdin if no files specified.

OPTIONS
    -i              Case-insensitive matching
    -v              Invert match (show non-matching lines)
    -c              Print only count of matching lines
    -n              Prefix each line with line number
    -l              Print only filenames containing matches
    -h              Suppress filename prefix in output
    -o              Print only the matching part of lines
    -E              Extended regex (default)
    -F              Fixed strings (literal match, no regex)
    -w              Match whole words only
    -x              Match whole lines only
    -q              Quiet mode (no output, exit status only)
    -m <num>        Stop after num matches
    -A <num>        Print num lines after each match
    -B <num>        Print num lines before each match
    -C <num>        Print num lines before and after (context)

EXAMPLES
    find . | grep users
        Find paths containing "users"

    grep -i error /var/log/app.log
        Case-insensitive search in file

    grep -n TODO *.ts
        Show line numbers for TODO comments

    grep -c error log1.txt log2.txt
        Count matches in each file

    grep -l password /etc/*
        List files containing "password"

    grep -v "^#" config.txt
        Show non-comment lines

    grep -w main *.c
        Match whole word "main"

    grep -C3 error app.log
        Show 3 lines of context around matches

    grep -o '[0-9]\+' data.txt
        Extract only numbers

    grep -F '*.txt' readme
        Literal match (no regex)

EXIT STATUS
    0       One or more matches found
    1       No matches found

SEE ALSO
    find, cat, sort
